n=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/upanamah.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Panamah</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(4/15/02 10:35:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehouseloungegeneraldiscussion.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=23310.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://nmcs.com/kingscourt/images/panamah_head.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Time investment VS long spawn times.  An Open Letter to </span><hr size=1> Well...<br><br>Actually I think they are both lousy models based upon the reasons you gave.  I wish I could suggest something better...<br><br>The type #1 encounter doesn't scale as servers get more crowded.  The competition just increases.<br><br>The type #2 encounter drives people to suffer endlessly from boredom and repetition with, potentially, nothing to show for many hours of frustration.<br><br>The ring type of thing could potentially be a lot of fun, but there's a couple of issues with it too.  You've got to bring a force large enough to handle the big guy but they'll overwhelm the ring in the earlier stages.  It'll be boring, laggy, etc.<br><br>What could be an improvement on the ring encounters is having it so groups can be working on various rings and come together for the final encounter.  Off in different parts of the dungeon.  Perhaps rather than &quot;surprise here's your boss mob!&quot; the penultimate spawn would be a mob that just stands around for a few minutes while you call the rest of the troops in.  Then you hand him something and spawn the big guy.<br><br>I think some of the competition over spawns will ease if they add more content and more servers and thin the population a bit.  Or if another game comes out that siphons people off.  Or they could make the spawn rates dependent on server populations or something.   <p><a href="http://nmcs.com/